search:.NET and EFCore Logging:logging i.content:
- Use `dotnet new console` to create a new .NET console application.
- Install the latest version of `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging` via NuGet:
  ```bash
  dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Logging
  ```
- Configure logging in your `Program.cs` or `Startup.cs` file:
  ```csharp
  var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
  builder.Services.AddLogging(builder =>
  {
      builder.ClearProviders();
      builder.AddConsole();
      builder.AddDebug();
  });
  ```
- Log messages using the logger instance:
  ```csharp
  private readonly ILogger<Program> _logger;

  public Program(ILogger<Program> logger)
  {
      _logger = logger;
  }

  _logger.LogInformation("User {UserName} with ID {UserId} logged in.", user, id);
  ```
- For structured logging, use named placeholders:
  ```csharp
  _logger.LogInformation("User {@User} logged in.", new { UserName = user, UserId = id });
  ```
- Centralize logs using Better Stack by configuring the provider and shipping logs to their service.

search:.NET and EFCore Logging:log4net w.content:
- Install log4net via NuGet: `dotnet add package log4net`
- Update appsettings.json to include log4net configuration:
```json
{
  "Logging": {
    "LogLevel": {
      "Default": "Information",
      "Microsoft.AspNetCore": "Warning"
    }
  },
  "log4net": {
    "root": {
      "level": "DEBUG",
      "appender-ref": "FileAppender"
    },
    "appender": {
      "FileAppender": {
        "type": "log4net.Appender.FileAppender",
        "file": "log-file.txt",
        "appendToFile": "true",
        "layout": {
          "type": "log4net.Layout.PatternLayout",
          "conversionPattern": "%date [%thread] %-5level %logger - %message%newline"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
- Configure log4net in Startup.cs:
```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    // Other service configurations...

    var logRepository = LogManager.GetRepository(Assembly.GetEntryAssembly());
    XmlConfigurator.Configure(logRepository, new FileInfo("log4net.config"));
}

public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    // Other middleware configurations...

    app.UseLogging();
}
```
- Create a log4net config file (e.g., `log4net.config`):
```xml
<log4net>
  <appender name="FileAppender" type="log4net.Appender.FileAppender">
    <file value="log-file.txt"/>
    <appendToFile value="true"/>
    <layout type="log4net.Layout.PatternLayout">
      <conversionPattern value="%date [%thread] %-5level %logger - %message%newline"/>
    </layout>
  </appender>
  <root>
    <level value="DEBUG"/>
    <appender-ref ref="FileAppender"/>
  </root>
</log4net>
```
- Use log4net in your code:
```csharp
using log4net;

public class MyService
{
    private static readonly ILog log = LogManager.GetLogger(typeof(MyService));

    public void DoWork()
    {
        try
        {
            // Your work here...
            log.Info("Doing some work");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            log.Error("Error occurred", ex);
        }
    }
}
```
- Ensure `log4net.config` is included in your project and copied to the output directory.

- Use `dotnet ef dbcontext scaffold` to generate EF Core models from an existing database.
- Example command: `dotnet ef dbcontext scaffold "Server=myServerAddress;Database=myDataBase;User Id=myUsername;Password=myPassword;" Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer -o Models`
- Ensure you have the latest version of Entity Framework Core installed via NuGet.
- Key config options for logging in `appsettings.json`:
  ```json
  {
    "Logging": {
      "LogLevel": {
        "Default": "Information",
        "Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Database.Command": "Debug"
      }
    }
  }
  ```
- For using log4net with EF Core, configure it in your project by adding necessary NuGet packages and setting up the logger provider.
- Example of configuring log4net:
  ```csharp
  var logRepository = LogManager.GetRepository(Assembly.GetEntryAssembly());
  BasicConfigurator.Configure(logRepository, new FlatFileAppender
  {
      FileName = "log-file.txt",
      Layout = new PatternLayout("%date [%thread] %-5level %logger - %message%newline")
  });
  ```
- Ensure your project references the appropriate log4net and EF Core packages.
- For detailed logging of EF queries, configure `Database.Log` in your DbContext:
  ```csharp
  protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
  {
      optionsBuilder.UseSqlServer("YourConnectionString")
                    .LogTo(Console.WriteLine, LogLevel.Information);
  }
  ```
- Always check the latest versions and documentation for any updates or changes in EF Core and log4net.
